{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515333"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:31:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:31:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12437"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12437"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.12,0.56,0.16,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77763"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4944"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63279"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"582"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"3399"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8560"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42757"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43887"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77763"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old man presents after vomiting up a small quantity of fresh blood. This is the first time this has happened. He does not have any other symptoms. His medical history includes type 2 diabetes for which he takes metformin. He has a 20-pack-year smoking history and drinks about four glasses of wine most evenings. On examination his blood pressure is 110/75 mmHg, pulse 91/min and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. His skin appears pale, he has gynaecomastia, his abdomen is mildly distended and he has some skin lesions on his trunk (Image). The rest of the examination is unremarkable. His haemoglobin is 89 g/L (130-175).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cryoprecipitate","Blood transfusion","Terlipressin","Propranolol","Tranexamic acid"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is very likely that this patient has cirrhosis, portal hypertension and oesophageal varices. Whilst he will require endoscopic assessment, he appears to be haemodynamically stable, so that this does not have to be an emergency procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe best treatment option for acute variceal bleed is \u003Cstrong\u003Eterlipressin. \u003C/strong\u003EIt is a synthetic vasopressin analogue that reduces portal blood flow or lowers intrahepatic resistance in turn lowering down the portal hypertension. It should be used with caution in patients with severe ischaemic heart disease (IHD) or peripheral vascular disease. Octreotide (mimics natural somatostatin pharmacologically) is the alternative pharmacological option for patients with IHD, peripheral vascular disease or in regions where terlipressin is not available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropranolol \u003C/strong\u003Eis a beta-blocker, used to lower portal venous pressure. It is either used as primary prevention of bleeding, if non-bleeding varices are identified at endoscopy or it is used as secondary prevention to prevent recurrent variceal bleed. It is usually not used in active variceal bleeds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid \u003C/strong\u003Eis an antifibrinolytic medication that works by blocking the breakdown of blood clots, thereby helping to control bleeding. It is sometimes used in adjunct to other therapies (terlipressin, endoscopic ligation or sclerotherapy), but it is not the first line of treatment for acute variceal bleeds making it the less likely option of choice in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood transfusion \u003C/strong\u003Emay be a necessary treatment for patients with variceal bleeding, as they may lose a significant amount of blood and require replacement of the blood components but the patient in this case is with Hb of 89 g/L, which does not require urgent transfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryoprecipitate \u003C/strong\u003Eis a frozen blood product prepared from blood plasma containing high level of clotting factors. It may be used as an adjunct treatment to help stop bleeding in case of a variceal bleed, but it is not the standard treatment and is used as second line after initial resuscitation and stabilisation of patient with pharmacological and endoscopic procedures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Terlipressin/octreotide is the pharmacological treatment of choice for variceal bleed."],"references":["Meseeha M, Attia M. Esophageal Varices. 2023 Aug 7. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 28846255. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28846255/","Ioannou G, Doust J, Rockey DC. Terlipressin for acute esophageal variceal hemorrhage. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2003;(1):CD002147. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD002147. PMID: 12535432. Avaialble from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12535432/","Zhou X, Tripathi D, Song T, Shao L, Han B, Zhu J, Han D, Liu F, Qi X. Terlipressin for the treatment of acute variceal bleeding: A systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials. Medicine (Baltimore). 2018 Nov;97(48):e13437. doi: 10.1097/MD.0000000000013437. PMID: 30508958; PMCID: PMC6283114. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30508958/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63279"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12437"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19230"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19230"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6c3fbe95-ce4a-4903-aa22-946801a4dee2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/6c3fbe95-ce4a-4903-aa22-946801a4dee2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":406}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63279"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T09:34:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T09:34:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4944"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77763"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"